Here’s a Rust function using generics to accept multiple data types:

rust
fn print_value<T: std::fmt::Display>(value: T) {
    println!("The value is: {}", value);
}

fn main() {
    print_value(42);          // Works with integers
    print_value("Hello");     // Works with string slices
    print_value(3.14);        // Works with floats
}


This function uses a generic type `T` constrained to types that implement the `Display` trait, allowing it to print any value. The `<T: std::fmt::Display>` syntax ensures the function can only accept types that can be formatted as strings. Testing this in a Rust environment helps solidify understanding of generics.
